{
  "doc_id": "7894",
  "text": "Melanoma incidence continues to increase year-on-year and is currently responsible for >80% of deaths from skin cancer [CITATION_1] . Melanomas are known to have the highest mutational load of all cancers. Among these, activating mutations in the serinethreonine kinase BRAF are the most prevalent and lead to the constitutive activation of the Ras-mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) pathway [CITATION_2] . A number of small molecule inhibitors, including vemurafenib and dabrafenib, are successful at treating BRAF mutant melanoma, albeit for only limited periods of time [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Indeed, long-term treatment has showed that the tumors often become resistant to such inhibitors [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Acquired BRAF inhibitor resistance is known to be mediated through several mechanisms with reactivation of the RAF-MEK-ERK signaling pathway being the most prevalent in >70% of cases. Increased RAF-MEK-ERK signal-ing can occur secondary to many events including the acquisition of NRAS mutations, mutations in MEK1/2, BRAF-splice mutants and through increased receptor tyrosine kinase signaling [CITATION_8] . Thus, despite the advances in the melanoma treatment, there is still an urgent need to identify new therapeutic strategies.",
